Comment: e4 open to me is the strongest move from any opponent.  d4 runs a close second choice to e4 open.  I am Black and my usual is the Caro Kann against e4....
...and so it is my most comfortable defense against the strongest White Open: e4.
A strong and expected response to the seemingly diminutive first move of Caro Kann Defense.
The usual thing to do here in Caro Kann...
A usual thing for White to do....
a usual thing for me to do...
the usual expected response to my usual.  Now comes the Caro Kann Defense to attack the knight:
A usual Caro Kann maneuver--but keep in mind Caro has more options in most times to usual moves by White to deal with the diminutive Caro Kann c6 defense to e4.....
My bishop is out and he needs to avoid capture.  I have to place him in a safe yet ready place for use.
Best place and the usual for Caro Kann.
This is an expected move for White to make.  In fact White has been doing the standard moves since e4 open on my favorite: The Caro Kann.
I inch forward with another seemingly diminutive move....

Usually I would have expected White to apply pressure King Side by going after my Q Bishop.  Not the case here. However, on the surface, this seems to be a safe move for White allowing 0-0 in the next move.  This is where White, who should be on the Offensive, becomes Defensive.  White should either attack and go out in a blaze of glory or resign or play a long game against a slow Black Defense like the Ruy Lopez.  Or Giuoco Piano. Or French Defense.  I am set in my ways.  The Caro Kann can suddenly turn the tables with attack at any time.
Castling for White in a protective ensconced corner of the board is now under contemplation....
White castles.
Standard for Caro Kann.
A build up around the White King while developing.

The other Knight coming into sequence and position with the other Knight coming across more laterally than vertically--in Caro Kann the Knights are used beyond the usual defenses.  They act in sequence like two rooks mated.
White is pushing Infantry at the expense of the range of his Bishops....
Since White is locking himself down into defense my only choice is to continue an attack.  It continues with another diminutive move common in the Caro Kann.
